<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12013h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12013h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12013h"> 13(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Muscle (little mouse) / beryl (briller) / horrid (chair de poule)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">M. Jean Paulhan a &eacute;crit une bien jolie brochure intitul&eacute;e <cite>Si les mots sont des signes</cite>. Il y rappelle que presque tout fut m&eacute;taphore &agrave; l&apos;origine et qu&apos;on serait bien ridicule d&apos;essayer de tout ramener &agrave; un sens pur, frais et pr&eacute;gnant. Pour moi, je n&apos;aurai pas, vous pensez bien, l&apos;ambition de prendre &lsquo;briller&rsquo; au sens de <i>luire comme un b&eacute;ryl</i> ni &lsquo;muscle&rsquo; au sens de <i>petit rat</i> ni &lsquo;horreur&rsquo; aus sens de <i>chair-de-poule</i>. C&apos;est pourtant le proc&eacute;d&eacute; du <font color="green">[227]</font> g&eacute;nial M. Claudel dans ses c&eacute;l&egrave;bres traductions. <br><font color="green">[M. Jean Paulhan has written a nice booklet under the title of <cite>Si les mots sont des signes</cite>. He reminds us that in the beginning everything was a metaphor and that it would be silly to reduce everything to a pure meaning, fresh and pregnant. As far as I&apos;m concernced, I do not have the ambition, to take <i>briller</i> in the sense of <i>luire comme un b&eacute;ryl</i> or <i>muscle</i> as meaning <i>petit rat</i> or <i>horreur</i> in the sense of <i>chair-de-poule</i>. And still that is the strategy of the brilliant M. Claudel in his famous translations.]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 227-8</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fr. <i>Chair de poule</i>: goose-bumps. &lsquo;Horrid&rsquo; comes from Latin <i>horrere</i>, to bristle. </mm> </dd></dl>
